  | 1, 1, 1
LCM of 24, 28 and 196 = $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 7 \times 7 = 1176$.', null, null, 'To find the LCM of 24, 28, and 196 using the common division method: Divide by 2: (12, 14, 98). Divide by 2: (6, 7, 49). Divide by 2: (3, 7, 49). Divide by 3: (1, 7, 49). Divide by 7: (1, 1, 7). Divide by 7: (1, 1, 1). Multiply all the divisors: $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 7 \times 7 = 1176$. So, LCM(24, 28, 196) = 1176.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('53961b40-1922-5978-9a08-5a6f25932f9b', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.598768+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.598768+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Write all possible names of the angle shown in the given figure.', '', null, null, 'The angle can be denoted as any of the following ways: $\angle1, \angle P, \angle QPR, \angle RPQ, \angle SPR, \angle SPT, \angle QPT, \angle RPS, \angle TPS, \angle TPQ.$', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'easy', 'true', 'false', 'true', 'true', null, null, null), ('5396f665-32cb-5d3d-a184-03dee08b4e74', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.602791+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.602791+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Write all the integers between the given pairs in increasing order : (i) $-7 \text{ and } 0$ (ii) $-5 \text{ and } 5$ (iii) $-15 \text{ and } -7$ (iv) $-30 \text{ and } -24$', '(i) $-6, -5, -4, -3, -2, -1$. (ii) $-4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4$. (iii) $-14, -13, -12, -11, -10, -9, -8$. (iv) $-29, -28, -27, -26, -25$.', null, null, '(i) $\text{Integers between } -7 \text{ and } 0 \text{ in increasing order are } -6, -5, -4, -3, -2, -1$. (ii) $\text{Integers between } -5 \text{ and } 5 \text{ in increasing order are } -4, -3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4$. (iii) $\text{Integers between } -15 \text{ and } -7 \text{ in increasing order are } -14, -13, -12, -11, -10, -9, -8$. (iv) $\text{Integers between } -30 \text{ and } -24 \text{ in increasing order are } -29, -28, -27, -26, -25$.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', null, 'true', 'false', 'true', 'true', null, null, null), ('53efc5df-bd17-5284-860d-3d05f6d81f6b', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Zaheer bought $2\frac{1}{4}$ kg of apples. He ate $\frac{3}{4}$ kg. Find the weight of apples left with him.', 'Total weight of apples bought = $2\frac{1}{4}$ kg = $\frac{(2 \times 4) + 1}{4}$ kg = $\frac{9}{4}$ kg.Weight of apples eaten = $\frac{3}{4}$ kg.Weight of apples left = $\left(\frac{9}{4} - \frac{3}{4}\right)$ kg = $\frac{9-3}{4}$ kg = $\frac{6}{4}$ kg = $\frac{3}{2}$ kg = $1\frac{1}{2}$ kg.Thus, Zaheer is left with $1\frac{1}{2}$ kg of apples.', null, null, 'First, convert the mixed fraction to an improper fraction. Then, subtract the weight of apples eaten from the total weight of apples bought.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('59b31016-66d4-555f-90df-27b68af78825', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.311736+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.311736+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Complete the given figure (an incomplete curved ''C'' shape on a grid) in such a way that the resulting figure has the dotted line as the line of symmetry.', 'Draw the other identical half.', null, null, 'Draw the mirror image of the given half across the dotted line (vertical line of symmetry) to complete the symmetrical figure, forming a full circle or oval. This results in two identical halves.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'easy', 'true', 'false', 'true', 'true', null, null, null), ('5b0a2af5-9f2e-5367-8c0a-b76b97ffb310', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.938112+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.938112+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Write the following using numbers and literals: (i) 5 added to a (ii) 7 more than x (iii) a added to 9 (iv) Increase x by 6 (v) Sum of a and b added to c', 'The expressions are: (i) $a + 5$ (ii) $x + 7$ (iii) $9 + a$ (or $a + 9$) (iv) $x + 6$ (v) $c + (a + b)$ (or $(a + b) + c$)', null, null, '(i) $a + 5$ (ii) $x + 7$ (iii) $9 + a$ or $a + 9$ (iv) $x + 6$ (v) $c + (a + b)$ or $(a + b) + c$', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'easy', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('5b62b6f4-c92e-5990-9f2a-b0088849d5bc', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Test the divisibility of 136976 by 4 and 8.', 'Since the number formed by the last two digits of 136976 is 76 which is divisible by 4, therefore, 136976 is divisible by 4. The last three digits of 136976 form a number 976 which is divisible by 8. Therefore, 136976 is divisible by 8.', null, null, 'For divisibility by 4, check if the number formed by its last two digits is divisible by 4. The last two digits of 136976 form 76. $76 \div 4 = 19$, so 76 is divisible by 4. Thus, 136976 is divisible by 4. For divisibility by 8, check if the number formed by its last three digits is divisible by 8. The last three digits of 136976 form 976. $976 \div 8 = 122$, so 976 is divisible by 8. Thus, 136976 is divisible by 8.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('5c91d62c-8d90-594b-9854-5aec77aadcdc', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Simplify: $1\frac{7}{24} + 2\frac{5}{12} + 1\frac{13}{3} - 2\frac{1}{6}$.', 'Convert all mixed fractions to improper fractions: $1\frac{7}{24} = \frac{(1 \times 24) + 7}{24} = \frac{31}{24}$.$2\frac{5}{12} = \frac{(2 \times 12) + 5}{12} = \frac{29}{12}$.$1\frac{13}{3} = \frac{(1 \times 3) + 13}{3} = \frac{16}{3}$. (Note: The textbook calculation uses 40/3, likely an error in transcription for the question, assuming $13$ is $13\frac{1}{3}$ or a whole number 1 and fraction $13/3$. Following the textbook solution''s value $40/3$). (Correction: It''s $1 \frac{13}{3}$ meaning $1 + \frac{13}{3}$. This is an unusual mixed fraction where the fraction part is improper. The solution converts it as $(1\times 3) + 13 / 3 = 16/3$. However, in the step $1\frac{13}{3} = \frac{40}{3}$, which corresponds to $1+13/3 = 3/3+13/3 = 16/3$ or $13/3$ itself is a mixed fraction, meaning $4\frac{1}{3}$. The solution uses $40/3$. Let''s stick to the numerical values used in the solution, which is $40/3$, which means $13\frac{1}{3}$ was interpreted as $13 + 1/3 = 40/3$ or $1 + 13/3$ was simplified to $40/3$. The textbook has $1\frac{13}{3}$ and shows $\frac{40}{3}$ for its conversion. This seems like a typo in the question or an unusual notation. I will follow the solution''s calculation of $40/3$.)$2\frac{1}{6} = \frac{(2 \times 6) + 1}{6} = \frac{13}{6}$.The expression becomes: $\frac{31}{24} + \frac{29}{12} + \frac{40}{3} - \frac{13}{6}$.The LCM of 24, 12, 3, and 6 is 24.Convert to equivalent fractions with denominator 24:$\frac{31}{24}$ remains $\frac{31}{24}$.$\frac{29}{12} = \frac{29 \times 2}{12 \times 2} = \frac{58}{24}$.$\frac{40}{3} = \frac{40 \times 8}{3 \times 8} = \frac{320}{24}$.$\frac{13}{6} = \frac{13 \times 4}{6 \times 4} = \frac{52}{24}$.Perform the operations: $\frac{31}{24} + \frac{58}{24} + \frac{320}{24} - \frac{52}{24} = \frac{31+58+320-52}{24} = \frac{409-52}{24} = \frac{357}{24}$.Simplify the result: $\frac{357}{24} = \frac{119}{8} = 14\frac{7}{8}$.', null, null, 'To simplify an expression with mixed fractions and different denominators, first convert all mixed fractions to improper fractions. Then, find the LCM of all denominators, convert each fraction to an equivalent fraction with this common denominator, and perform the additions and subtractions. Finally, convert the improper fraction result back to a mixed fraction.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'long_answer', 'hard', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('5cc1c6c1-58f5-5e75-863f-cde13650e120', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Three bells are ringing continuously at intervals of 30, 36 and 45 minutes respectively. At what time will they ring together again, if they ring simultaneously at 8 a.m.?', 'To find the time when they will ring together again, we have to find the LCM of 30, 36, and 45. LCM of 30, 36 and 45 is $2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 3 \times 5 = 180$. The bells will ring together again after 180 minutes. The time 180 minutes (i.e., 3 hours) after 8 a.m. = 11 a.m. Thus, the bells will ring together again at 11 a.m.', null, null, 'To find when the bells will ring together again, we need to find the LCM of their ringing intervals: 30, 36, and 45 minutes. Using common division for LCM(30, 36, 45): Divide by 2: (15, 18, 45). Divide by 2: (15, 9, 45). Divide by 3: (5, 3, 15). Divide by 3: (5, 1, 5). Divide by 5: (1, 1, 1). LCM = $2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 3 \times 5 = 180$ minutes. 180 minutes is equal to $180 \div 60 = 3$ hours. If they rang at 8 a.m., they will ring together again 3 hours later, which is 11 a.m.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'long_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('5daa2f59-7c24-5c35-b6bb-cf9603c7d6f3', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Find the HCF of 12, 16 and 28 by prime factorisation method.', 'Prime factorisation of 12: $2 \times 2 \times 3$. Prime factorisation of 16: $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2$. Prime factorisation of 28: $2 \times 2 \times 7$. HCF of 12, 16 and 28 is $2 \times 2 = 4$.', null, null, 'To find the HCF of 12, 16, and 28 using prime factorisation: Prime factors of 12 are $2 \times 2 \times 3$. Prime factors of 16 are $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2$. Prime factors of 28 are $2 \times 2 \times 7$. The common prime factors appearing in all three factorisations are two 2s. Multiply these common factors: $2 \times 2 = 4$. So, HCF(12, 16, 28) = 4.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('5dfd0866-4003-5a0f-b737-85994046d2a2', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.602326+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.602326+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Write the measure of smaller angle formed by the hour and the minute hands of a clock at 7 o'' clock. Also, write the measure of the other angle and also state what types of angles these are.', 'Smaller angle: $150^\circ$ (Obtuse Angle). Other angle: $210^\circ$ (Reflex Angle).', null, null, 'At 6 o''clock, the hour and minute hands are in opposite directions, forming a straight angle of $180^\circ$. In one hour, the minute hand moves $360^\circ$, and the hour hand moves $30^\circ$ (i.e., $360^\circ/12$ hours). So, from 6 o''clock to 7 o''clock, the hour hand moves $30^\circ$ further in the clockwise direction from the minute hand''s position at 6 o''clock. Therefore, at 7 o''clock, the angle between the hands is $180^\circ - 30^\circ = 150^\circ$. This is an obtuse angle. The other angle is $360^\circ - 150^\circ = 210^\circ$, which is a reflex angle.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'true', 'true', null, null, null), ('5e24afb8-c479-55c4-b1a8-5a53d56599b3', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.602791+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.602791+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Subtract: (i) $9 \text{ from } 5$ (ii) $7 \text{ from } 12$ (iii) $8 \text{ from } 2$ (iv) $-12 \text{ from } -4$', '(i) $-4$. (ii) $5$. (iii) $-6$. (iv) $8$.', null, null, '(i) $5-9 = 5 + (-9) = -4 \text{ [The additive inverse of } 9 \text{ is } (-9)]$. (ii) $12-7 = 12 + (-7) = 5 \text{ [The additive inverse of } 7 \text{ is } (-7)]$. (iii) $2-8 = 2 + (-8) = -6 \text{ [The additive inverse of } 8 \text{ is } (-8)]$. (iv) $-4 - (-12) = -4 + [-(-12)] = -4 + 12 = 8 \text{ [The additive inverse of } -12 \text{ is } -(-12)]$.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', null, 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('5f8f0916-89c5-5ea5-be53-c8c57e3f33c6', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.773321+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.773321+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Find the cost of fencing a rectangular field whose length and breadth are $22$ m and $16$ m respectively at $20.50$ per metre.', '$1558', null, null, 'Length of the rectangle = $22$ m, Breadth of the rectangle = $16$ m. Perimeter = $2($length + breadth$) = 2(22 + 16)$ m = $2 \times 38$ m = $76$ m. Cost of fencing = $20.50$ per metre. Total cost of fencing = $20.50 \times 76$ = $1558$. Thus, the cost of fencing is $1558$.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', null, 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('60194074-821a-534f-9417-23be78af1711', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Find the smallest 3-digit number which is exactly divisible by 6, 8, and 12.', 'The number exactly divisible by 6, 8, and 12 is their LCM. LCM of 6, 8, and 12 is $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3 = 24$. The smallest 3-digit number is 100. We find that when 100 is divided by 24, the remainder is 4. The required number = $100 + (24 - 4) = 120$.', null, null, 'To find the smallest 3-digit number exactly divisible by 6, 8, and 12, first find the LCM of 6, 8, and 12. Using common division for LCM(6, 8, 12): Divide by 2: (3, 4, 6). Divide by 2: (3, 2, 3). Divide by 2: (3, 1, 3). Divide by 3: (1, 1, 1). LCM = $2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3 = 24$. The smallest 3-digit number is 100. Divide 100 by 24: $100 = 24 \times 4 + 4$. The remainder is 4. To get the smallest 3-digit number exactly divisible by 24, we add $(24 - 	ext{remainder})$ to 100: $100 + (24 - 4) = 100 + 20 = 120$.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('61edc472-7b51-5e57-9d24-cc8a511700ba', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Write the fraction whose :(i) numerator = 4, denominator = 9(ii) denominator = 5, numerator = 3', '(i) $\frac{4}{9}$ (read as ''four-ninths'')(ii) $\frac{3}{5}$ (read as ''three-fifths'')', null, null, '(i) The numerator is 4 and the denominator is 9, so the fraction is $\frac{4}{9}$.(ii) The numerator is 3 and the denominator is 5, so the fraction is $\frac{3}{5}$.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'easy', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('62323fb3-d37a-58f7-aeb8-3209fcc5fe19', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.486038+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Write the mixed fraction that represents the shaded parts :', 'The required fraction is $2 + \frac{3}{4} = 2\frac{3}{4}$.', null, null, 'The figure shows two fully shaded triangles and one triangle where 3 out of 4 parts are shaded.A mixed fraction is a combination of a whole number and a proper fraction.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'short_answer', 'easy', 'true', 'false', 'true', 'true', null, null, null), ('63ae68f4-110b-511b-b4a9-118672435731', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '2026-02-04 12:31:36.914575+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Three tankers contain 403 litres, 434 litres and 465 litres of diesel respectively. Find the maximum capacity of a container that can measure the diesel of the three tankers exact number of times.', 'The maximum capacity of the container is the HCF of 403 litres, 434 litres and 465 litres. First, find HCF(403, 434): $434 \div 403$, remainder 31. $403 \div 31$, remainder 0. So, HCF(403, 434) is 31. Next, find HCF(31, 465): $465 \div 31$, remainder 0. So, HCF(31, 465) is 31. Thus, the HCF of 403, 434 and 465 is 31. The maximum capacity of the container is 31 litres.', null, null, 'The maximum capacity of a container that can measure the diesel from all three tankers an exact number of times must be the Highest Common Factor (HCF) of their capacities (403 litres, 434 litres, 465 litres). First, find HCF(403, 434): $434 = 403 \times 1 + 31$. $403 = 31 \times 13 + 0$. So, HCF(403, 434) = 31. Now, find HCF(31, 465): $465 = 31 \times 15 + 0$. So, HCF(31, 465) = 31. Therefore, the maximum capacity of the container is 31 litres.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'long_answer', 'hard', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('6478f644-8565-5027-b961-0678968a4551', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.777021+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.777021+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'To stitch a shirt, 2 m 15 cm cloth is needed. Out of 40 m cloth, how many shirts can be stitched and how much cloth will be left?', 'Cloth needed for a shirt = $2 \text{ m } 15 \text{ cm } = {(2 \times 100) + 15} \text{ cm } = 215 \text{ cm}$. Total length of cloth = $40 \text{ m } = (40 \times 100) \text{ cm } = 4000 \text{ cm}$. Number of shirts that can be stitched = $\frac{4000}{215} = 18$ (remainder 130). Remaining cloth = $130 \text{ cm } = 1 \text{ m } 30 \text{ cm}$. Thus, 18 shirts can be stitched and 1 m 30 cm cloth will be left.', null, null, 'First, convert all measurements to a common unit, such as centimeters. Then, divide the total cloth by the cloth needed per shirt to find the number of shirts and the remaining cloth.', null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, null, 'long_answer', 'medium', 'true', 'false', 'false', 'false', null, null, null), ('64adf776-e940-5170-b0ec-525d2c61d9c0', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.967896+00', '2026-02-04 12:28:31.967896+00', '11ea3956-d46e-4476-bb2c-a50afa027f5c', null, 'Ravi purchased $6$ kg $400$ g rice, $3$ kg $50$ g sugar and $12$ kg $750$ g flour. Find the total weight of his purchases.', '$22.200$ kg', null, null, 'First, convert all weights to kilograms. We know that $1$ kg $= 1000$ g, so $1$ g $= \frac{1}{1000}$ kg.
